An fisheye lens, it's perhaps a bit too much for a niche.
We learn from our mistakes.
I should have known, since I already made one with a "normal" lens.
I'll tell you more this weekend once I've installed the second one I made.
Let's say the birds will have a better Internet connection than mine in 2015.
Or at least, that's the goal.
The box that already contains a birdhouse benefits from the home's Wi-Fi.
There's still work to do to connect the other one.
Well, I mounted the other birdhouse during the day. Here's what it looks like in its proper place in the garden.
But, little flashback: "What's inside?" I don't hear myself asking.
At the top is one of these ESP32 modules with a fisheye camera and an infrared LED that I picked up from a Raspberry Pi device.
If this plastic box has an odd shape, it's because of the pivoting side panel of the birdhouse. I bought it like that and couldn't modify it, so I had to design my installation around it.
Since there's no electricity in the garden, the whole setup is powered by a solar panel and a 2,600 mAh 18650 cell.
I didn't photograph the cell or the charger, but here's a photo of the panel.
The gray box suspended on the side of the birdhouse holds the battery.
At full charge, it gives me about 4 hours of power.
I call it a feature. So the birds can also have a bit of privacy.
Initially, I didn't know if the Internet connection in our garden would be good enough for this setup. The old access points I replaced last autumn wouldn't have been sufficient.
But the new ones cover the area well.
It's almost disappointing because I had planned to mount a TP-Link cpe210 on the roof and aim it downward toward the garden.
I could always do it when I install more camera birdhouses, especially in areas far from the house, I might need it.
Now, for reasons that I can't figure out yet, the camera is offline. It turned off just an hour after sunset.
The battery charge may have stopped three hours before sunset due to a lack of light.
Maybe it couldn't charge fully in a little less than half a day.
I'll see what happens tomorrow.
I don't have a battery telemetry system. I might add one during a future revision.
A few more sensors would be nice, I think.
And maybe a battery capable of lasting all night, at least on paper.
Oh, and another lens.
The fisheye is too much.
But I'm already looking at parts on Digikey, so I might just make a custom PCB for this use case.
Or not. We'll see.
And, it's still offline.
Great.
Considering the solar panels installed on the house, the sun is really high only for about 90 minutes.
Let's wait another hour or two to see what happens or not.
Still offline.
Nothing is ever simple.
In fact, on the USB-C board I was using to connect the battery charger, the 5V and ground were reversed.
I swapped the wires, and now I have a charging indicator.
The ESP didn't connect right away, let's wait a few minutes.
An hour later: still offline.
It seems like it's restarting in a loop and triggering the Tasmota reset functionality.
I think the panel is just bad. I ordered a bigger one, hoping it works.
Look what I found in the workshop.
A 24 V panel. Unfortunately, the sun is so low (and partly hidden by a tree) that it drops to almost nothing as soon as I use it.
I think I'm going to wait until tomorrow to see if it's sufficient for this installation or if I need the best panel I ordered.
According to Amazon, I bought the panel in 2021, and it should generate 12 V at a maximum of 1.2 A.
So, either something is wrong with this panel or with my multimeter, or they have changed the specs.
Good news, everyone !
They changed the specifications and the one I have is H.S.
The titles of the old and new specifications mention a 12 V, 10 W panel.
That's why I don't delete my old emails.
Hey, look: the thing reconnected for about half a minute about an hour ago.
Maybe the panel charged the battery just enough for 38 seconds of power. That would have taken a bit more than two hours.
Guess what: the weather is cloudy today. So I'm not sure if this solar panel (probably broken) is capable of generating enough energy to do anything.
Let's see.
Latest news: I installed the new panel and it seems to be working.
If it turns out everything goes off at sunset, but let's see.
By the way, I'm using the ping integration in Home Assistant to check if it's connected or not.
The round-trip time is 102 ms. Not great, but not too bad.
